.TH FAR 1 "2026-05-22" "1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
far \- find and replace text across files matching a filename glob
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B far
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fIglob\fR \fIfind\fR \fIreplace\fR [\fIroot\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B far
searches recursively under a root directory for files whose names match a
given glob pattern and whose contents contain a search term, then performs
an in-place substitution replacing all occurrences of the search term with
the replacement string.
.PP
.B far
uses
.BR rg (1)
to locate matching files (fast, parallel, gitignore-aware) and
.BR sed (1)
to perform the substitution.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.B glob
A filename glob pattern used to restrict which files are searched.
Examples: \fI*.cpp\fR, \fI*.{h,cpp}\fR, \fIMakefile\fR.
.TP
.B find
The text or basic regular expression to search for within each file.
.TP
.B replace
The replacement string. Backreferences are not supported.
.TP
.B root
The directory to search under. Defaults to the current directory (\fI.\fR).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-y
Skip the confirmation prompt and apply changes immediately.
.TP
.B \-n
Dry run. Print the list of files that would be modified but make no changes.
.TP
.B \-b
Write a backup of each modified file with a \fI.bak\fR suffix before applying changes.
.TP
.B \-h
Print a help message and exit.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Invalid arguments.
.TP
.B 2
No files matched the given glob and search term.
.TP
.B 3
User aborted at the confirmation prompt.
.SH EXAMPLES
Replace all occurrences of \fIOldClass\fR with \fINewClass\fR in C++ source files
under the current directory:
.PP
.RS
.nf
far '*.cpp' 'OldClass' 'NewClass'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Same, but restricted to the \fI./src\fR subtree:
.PP
.RS
.nf
far '*.cpp' 'OldClass' 'NewClass' ./src
.fi
.RE
.PP
Skip the confirmation prompt:
.PP
.RS
.nf
far -y '*.txt' 'foo' 'bar'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Dry run -- show affected files without modifying them:
.PP
.RS
.nf
far -n '*.h' 'TODO' 'FIXME'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Replace with backups:
.PP
.RS
.nf
far -b '*.cpp' 'OldClass' 'NewClass'
.fi
.RE
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.BR rg (1)
ripgrep, used for fast parallel file content search.
Available at https://github.com/BurntSushi/ripgrep or via your package manager.
.TP
.BR sed (1)
Used for in-place substitution. Standard on all POSIX systems.
.SH CAVEATS
The
.I find
and
.I replace
arguments are passed directly to
.BR sed (1)
as a substitution expression. Strings containing
.B /
or
.B &
must be escaped. Complex regex features (lookaheads, backreferences) are not supported.
.PP
Without
.B \-b
there is no undo. Use
.B \-n
to preview before committing.
.SH AUTHOR
Written by Christian Schladetsch.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR rg (1),
.BR fd (1),
.BR sed (1),
.BR find (1)
